05347nam a22010455i 9780520928312DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021697102  a97805209283127 a10.1525/97805209283122doi  a(DE-B1597)520818  a(OCoLC)437144833  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aTX723 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a641.51 aMartino of Como, Maestro, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Art of Cooking :bThe First Modern Cookery Book /cMaestro Martino of Como; ed. by Luigi Ballerini. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in Food and Culture ;v140 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMaestro Martino of Como has been called the first celebrity chef, and his extraordinary treatise on Renaissance cookery, The Art of Cooking, is the first known culinary guide to specify ingredients, cooking times and techniques, utensils, and amounts. This vibrant document is also essential to understanding the forms of conviviality developed in Central Italy during the Renaissance, as well as their sociopolitical implications. In addition to the original text, this first complete English translation of the work includes a historical essay by Luigi Ballerini and fifty modernized recipes by acclaimed Italian chef Stefania Barzini. The Art of Cooking, unlike the culinary manuals of the time, is a true gastronomic lexicon, surprisingly like a modern cookbook in identifying the quantity and kinds of ingredients in each dish, the proper procedure for cooking them, and the time required, as well as including many of the secrets of a culinary expert. In his lively introduction, Luigi Ballerini places Maestro Martino in the complicated context of his time and place and guides the reader through the complexities of Italian and papal politics. Stefania Barzini's modernized recipes that follow the text bring the tastes of the original dishes into line with modern tastes. Her knowledgeable explanations of how she has adapted the recipes to the contemporary palate are models of their kind and will inspire readers to recreate these classic dishes in their own kitchens. Jeremy Parzen's translation is the first to gather the entire corpus of Martino's legacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCookingzItalyvEarly works to 1800. 0aCooking, ItalianvEarly works to 1800. 0aCooking. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aart of cooking.  acelebrity chef.  acentral italy.  acomo.  acooking.  acoppiette.  aculinary manuals.  aculinary.  afood history.  afood studies.  afood.  agame animals.  agastronomy.  ahare.  ahistorical food.  aitalian cuisine.  aitalian culture.  aitalian history.  aitaly.  amaestro martino.  ameat pie.  amodern italian.  anonfiction.  apapal politics.  arecipes.  arenaissance cooking.  arenaissance food.  arenaissance recipes.  astefania barzini.  atomacelli.  atorte.  atraditional italian recipes.  atraditional recipes.  aveal mortadella.  aveal.  awestern cuisine.  awild boar.1 aBallerini, Luigi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBallerini, Luigi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarzini, Stefania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParzen, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042